
[1]celestins

   CELESTINS, n. A religious order, so named from Pope Celestin. They have
   ninety-six convents in Italy, and twenty-one in France. They rise two
   hours after midnight to say matins. They eat no flesh, except when
   sick, and fast often. Their habit is a white gown, a capuche and a
   black scapulary.
